    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-01-25T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-01-25T06:00:00-05:00" n="77"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d77">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851G.711/1–2547: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-01-25T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 25, 1947—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>336. Question of censorship in Indochina discussed with Baudet<note n="43"
                        xml:id="d77fn43">Philippe Baudet, Director of the Asiatic Division of the
                        French Foreign Office.</note> last evening. He said that a message had been
                    sent to d’Argenlieu pointing out the possible injurious effect on American
                    public opinion of censorship policy recently adopted. Baudet added, however,
                    that Foreign Office did not feel it had the authority to issue instructions to
                    d’Argenlieu on a matter which is considered to be a military question.<note
                        n="44" xml:id="d77fn44">Despatch 187, February 19, from Saigon, gave a
                        detailed account of steps taken since mid-November to control the
                        dissemination of information in Indochina and the flow of information out of
                        Indochina. As the Chief of the Division of Southeast Asian Affairs (Moffat)
                        commented in a memorandum of March 7, “the picture of the censorship
                        exercised by the French as it appears in this despatch is that of a
                        totalitarian regime at its worst.” The Department on April 28 commended the
                        writer of the despatch for compiling “this discerning and comprehensive
                        report on a subject of the greatest interest to the Department.”
                        (851G.918/2–1947)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
